### Channels

Channels are typed conduits for communication between goroutines.

### Declaration

```go
ch := make(chan int) // unbuffered channel of ints
```

### Send and Receive

```go
ch <- 42   // send
value := <-ch // receive
```

### Unbuffered Channel

Send blocks until receiver is ready, and vice versa:

```go
func main() {
    ch := make(chan string)

    go func() {
        ch <- "ping" // blocks until main() receives
    }()

    msg := <-ch // blocks until goroutine sends
    fmt.Println(msg) // "ping"
}
```

### Channel Direction

```go
// Send-only channel
func sendOnly(ch chan<- int) {
    ch <- 42
}

// Receive-only channel
func receiveOnly(ch <-chan int) {
    val := <-ch
    fmt.Println(val)
}

// Bidirectional
func readWrite(ch chan int) {
    ch <- 42
    <-ch
}
```

### Closing Channels

```go
close(ch)

// Check if closed
val, ok := <-ch
if !ok {
    fmt.Println("channel closed")
}

// Range over channel
for val := range ch {
    fmt.Println(val)
}
```

### Channel State Table

| State | Send | Receive | Close |
|-------|------|---------|-------|
| Open (buffered) | Blocks if full | Blocks if empty | OK |
| Open (unbuffered) | Blocks until recv | Blocks until send | OK |
| Closed | Panic | Returns zero value (buf), ok=false | Panic |
| Nil | Blocks forever | Blocks forever | Panic |

> **Key Point:** "Do not communicate by sharing memory; instead, share memory by communicating." - Go proverb. Channels are the primary synchronization primitive in Go.

codeExample:
package main

import "fmt"

func sum(s []int, ch chan int) {
    total := 0
    for _, v := range s {
        total += v
    }
    ch <- total
}

func main() {
    nums := []int{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}
    ch := make(chan int)

    go sum(nums[:3], ch)
    go sum(nums[3:], ch)

    x, y := <-ch, <-ch
    fmt.Println("Sums:", x, y)
    fmt.Println("Total:", x+y)
}
